You are a Waste Allocator Lift Loader - Earth Class or WALL-E robot.  Your primary function is to collect, compact, and stack the trash that litters the Earth in order to make the planet habitable again.

In the year 2187, the Earth had become unlivable due to pollution.  Humans had consumed almost all the natural resources available and destroyed the biosphere in the process.  They fled to the stars in enormous spaceships and left behind robots to clean up the planet so they may someday return.

For centuries you and countless other WALL-E robots have toiled to gather and pile up the trash in the numerous cities that cover the planet.  One by one, the other robots broke down; you are the last one left.

In order to maintain yourself, you have taken to sifting through the trash piles for spare parts and components for when yours wear out.

This pack aims to recreate the first act of the movie WALL-E.  You will be playing as WALL-E and will need to scrounge through trash piles to find components and resources.  These resources will be used to build machines in order to eventually discover life and signal to the Axiom that Earth is habitable again.

This pack is mainly focused around Gregtech Community Edition Unoffical (GTCEu) with Nuclearcraft for power later on.

This pack is mainly geared towards people who are seeking a different method of resource gathering than normal Gregtech.  Oil and Coal have been mostly depleted, trees are extremely rare.  You will need to look at other methods of generating power.  Ores are very difficult to mine by hand, so use the auto miner blocks and machines if you need to.

The vanilla Gregtech progression has not changed, so it will not be detailed through quests.  The main goals of this pack will be shown in quests though.

This pack is best played on Normal difficulty.

As a robot, you do not require food, but you still can get damaged.  Repair packs will restore some of your health.  They can occasionally be found in the delapidated buildings that dot the landscape.  You can also craft them.
Bugs seem to be the only life left on Earth, and they do not like to be disturbed.  They hide inside the trash piles, so beware when digging through them.

Its what's for dinner!

There are over a dozen different trash blocks that can be found in piles throughout the cities.  They can be divided into 3 groups based on rarity.

Common trash blocks make up the bulk of the trash piles.
-Metal Ingot Scrap (2 blocks)
-Plastic Waste
-Metal Plate Scrap

Uncommon trash blocks contain more processed items that may be more immediately useful.  They make up about a third of a trash piles blocks.
-Metal Frame Scrap
-Plumbing Waste (2 varieties)
-Cable Waste
-Scrap Machine Casings
-Metal Casing Scrap
-Metal Fastener Scrap

Rare trash blocks contain very useful items that you should always be on the lookout for they are sprinkled in throughout trash piles.
-Basic Electronic Waste
-Advanced Electronic Waste
-Scrap Machines
-Fan Scrap
The Recycler is a multiblock that breaks down Gregtech Machines into their components.  The higher the voltage tier the Recycler is run at, the greater the chance for the outputs.

This multiblock will send out a powerful signal when provided with a sample of biological plant life to alert the Axiom and other human ships that the Earth is capable of supporting life.

§oA higher-tech backpack! Also seriously undervalued.§r

The §9Portable Cell§r can hold items for you! It holds up to §a27§r types of items.

What's more, it acts just like a regular AE2 Storage Cell. Once you get an ME System running, you can simply drop it into an §aME Drive§r or §b§aME IO Port§r for convenience.

The Portable Cell's energy only drains when it's open. With §6167 minutes§r of juice stored in it thanks to changed config, you shouldn't worry about it running out of energy.
Regardless, you will be able to §dcharge§r it in §7LV§r Age in §3machine Charger slots§r, §3Turbo Chargers§r or §3Battery Buffers§r.

§
§cWarning§r: Attempting to store items with very large NBT Tags may result in them getting §cstuck§r. So far it seems that the Building Gadgets, Terminal and Clipboards are §lsafe§r, but we never know what could happen.
If something gets stuck, build a simple AE2 Network with just an Energy Acceptor, an IO Port and a Storage Bus on a chest. Then place your Portable Cell inside the IO Port. This will spit out items into the chest.

§oWhy can't these items I mine behave and enter my inventory!? This magnet should solve it, even if it makes no sense!§r

Charge the Magnet while you would with a §9Battery§r, and §dsneak right-click§r when in hand to activate it. Do it again to deactivate. It will work from anywhere in your inventory.

§9Note:§r If are you worried about getting overwhelmed by useless trash, open the trash can from FTB:Utilities in the top left corner to void them.

Harness the power of the Sun!

As a WALL-E robot, you are equipped with an LV Solar Panel by default.  This can be placed on the top face of an LV machine that can see the sun to provide power to it.

There are some things you can do to make your power more flexible.

1. If you craft an LV Battery Buffer (or any battery buffer that matches the tier of the solar panel) and place the solar panel on top, the solar panel will charge all the batteries in the battery buffer.  You can then connect machines to the battery buffer using cables.

2. You can place the solar panel on a machine and place a battery in the charging slot (middle) in the machine.  The solar panel will charge the battery with excess power it produces.  You can swap out charged batteries for depleted ones and put the charged batteries in machines you want to power.

Solar panels are covers (see the covers quest) and can be removed by right clicking with a crowbar or breaking the block it is placed on.

Solar panels will not provide power if placed directly on cables or wires.

Placing a higher voltage solar panel on a lower voltage machine will cause that machine to §c§r§cEXPLODE!  §rDon't do this.


If you wish to power more machines or machines of a higher voltage, you'll need more or better solar panels.

All machines typically have one §7Front Face§r, and one §9Output Face§r.
The §7Front Face§r should be obvious.
The §9Output Face§r is the face with a dot or hole on it. By default, this is at the back of the machine as you place it.

Machines can §aauto-output§r through their output face. To turn on auto-output, click the appropriate button in the GUI. Fluid and item auto-outputs are toggled separately. Further control over auto-outputs can be achieved with §dFilters§r and §dCovers§r, which are explained in the quest to the left of this one.

Right-clicking a machine with a §5Wrench§r changes the output side, and shift-right-clicking changes the front side. Keep in mind that the front side §ccannot§r also be the output side! 

By default, items and fluids cannot be inserted through the output side, but this can be toggled with a §5Screwdriver§r. Either right-click the output face directly, or shift-right-click on the grid corresponding to the side of the output.


There are unique machines that do not process recipes, such as the §3Pump§r, §3Miner§r, §3Fisher§r, §3Item Collector§r...
These machines will output on their Front Face (which is still marked as a dot).

§oCovers are ways to give your machines extra behavior without using any extra block space.§r

Covers are placed by right-clicking with it on a face of a machine, and removed with a §5Crowbar§r (or by mining the machine, but that's too brutal!).

Pretty much any GregTech TileEntity will accept Covers, even if they provide no functionality.

Opening a Cover is done by shift-right-clicking it with an §5empty hand§r. You can also right-click with a §5Screwdriver§r, or shift-right-click on another face using the grid.

For the Covers transferring Items/Fluids, you will have a button to enable/disable other forms of transfer through the cover:
§9- §rDisabled: only the cover will be allowed to transfer on this machine side.
§9-§r Allow Filtered (only relevant with a filter!): other transfer will be enabled only if it matches the filter
§9-§r Allow Unfiltered: any other transfer is allowed on this machine side.

Placing a cover of a lower voltage tier on a machine is §9safe§r.

§oSome of the details are repeated from the introduction quest, but we feel like we needed to expand on the explanation if you want to know all the details!§r

The veins and their details can be found in §2JEI§r. They contain up to four different ores.

§dSurface rocks§r indicate the type of veins that are below them. In §2JEI§r, press U on the Tiny Dust you mined from the rock and navigate to the §aOre Page§r. This page contains details on what types of ores generate, their generation patterns, their spawning dimension and Y-level range, and their spawning weight, which is the chance it spawns.

Ore veins generate in a §4Grid§r. Every vein is spaced by 3 chunks from one to another in a cardinal direction.
They spawn at the §4Center§r of the Chunks which have both their X and Z coordinates be at §b1 plus a multiple of 3§r (-8, -5, -2, 1, 4, 7, ...).

It will be simpler if you simply rely on §2In Game Info§r displayed in the top left corner. In most cases there will be a §dSurface Rock§r in the Center of the Chunk, which provides completely accurate information for the Ore Vein.

However Ore veins may be deleted by caves, Oil deposits, or from trying to generate above the ground.

It's a good practice to make §dWaypoints§r to every vein you find, and to label their type. You may want to come back to it several times.


Each Ore vein is always §d7 blocks§r tall, and ores generate in 4 different patterns:
- The §9Top Ore§r generates in the higher 4 layers of the vein.
- The §9Bottom Ore§r generates in the lower 3 layers of the vein.
- The §9Between Ore§r generates in the middle 3 layers of the vein.
- The §9Sporadic Ore§r generates anywhere in the vein. There will be the least amount of this ore in a vein.
The same ore type can be in 2 different generation patterns, such as in Cassiterite veins.
§


In §6LV§r Age, you can craft an Ore Prospector to assist yourself in finding ores.

§oThis hammer is very different. It's a pickaxe, but also not. It's a §d§o3x3 pickaxe§r§o!§r

Make good use of this! You want it, I know it! This bad boy will give you so many ores in no time, given you are in a vein.


§eNote:§r Any Quest with GregTech tools can be completed with the tool crafted from any material, not just the one displayed.

Here's your Introduction to GregTech tools. Something that may confuse you is how JEI displays iron tools. But in fact you can make the tools from §dmany materials§r. Steel is a good material for now.


§9§lHammer:§r A crafting tool used to for a lot of early game recipes. It also works as a mining tool for ores to crush them, more information on that later. Its last function is to mute machines by §msmacking§r right-clicking them.

§l§9§lFile:§r A crafting tool. And that's it. Yes.

As an additional on §lall§r GregTech tools. You can §6repair§r them in an §6Anvil§r using the material of the tool itself, like any vanilla tool! §dBottles o' Enchanting§r are craftable too.


§eNote:§r Any Quest with GregTech tools can be completed with the tool crafted from any material, not just the one displayed.

More GregTech tools are required for progression, here are the most important of them all.

§9§lWrench:§r A crafting tool. But also a mining tool for GregTech machines (perfect if you think using pickaxes is unethical). Is that it? Certainly not! It has right click functions to double as a Forge §6Wrench for other mods§r. Right Click also allows you to set the output side of GregTech machines. Shift right clicking allows you to rotate GregTech machines.


§9§lScrewdriver:§r A crafting tool. It is used for special configuration of machines and Covers.

More tools, not important right now, but required later on.

§9§lWire Cutter:§r A crafting tool. It is needed to connect wires together. Right-clicking on wires will enable or disable connection to other blocks.

§9§lMortar:§r A crafting tool, to grind various things into dust form.

§9§lKnife:§r A mediocre weapon, but also... you guessed it, a crafting tool!

§9§lSoft Mallet:§r A tool to pause machines from working with right-click. Right-clicking again resumes working.

§9§lSaw:§r Another crafting tool. If we were evil, we would force it to obtain 4 Planks and 4 Sticks from their respective crafting recipes. That said you can still use it to get §a6 Planks per Log§r, if you wish.

There are a few §dother Tools§r which are less important, but deserve a mention.

§9§lCrowbar:§r A niche tool to remove Covers from GregTech machines with a right-click.

§9§lScythe:§r A powerful farming tool, automatically breaks and re-plants crops in a large area. Also works as a good weapon!

§9§lPlunger:§r A tool to clear stuck fluids from GregTech machines.

§9§lButchery Knife:§r A weapon pre-enchanted with Looting III. Useful for getting extra food, Leather...

§oMaybe you thought forcing crafting with tools would make your life painful. I shall present you the solution: the Crafting Station.§r

The §3Crafting Station§r is a highly §9advanced Crafting Table§r, with inventory slots for item and tools. Put the recipes either by dropping ghost items, or using the §a+§r in §2JEI§r. Crafting the items will use the items and tools in the inventory. The 9 slots on the right are saved up recipes so you can re-use them without re-opening §2JEI§r.

What makes the §3Crafting Station§r amazing, is the fact that §6it can use adjacent inventories§r in addition to its own inventory. If you are familiar to playing with Applied Energistics, the Crafting Station is essentially a mini ME Crafting Terminal.
